01:15:13.051 --> 01:15:17.811
It looks a little bit more like Streamlit, less like Dash.

01:15:17.811 --> 01:15:22.131
The core mode is the more traditional route where you have a variable that defines all

01:15:22.131 --> 01:15:26.890
of the inputs in a separate section that defines all of the reactive calculations and

01:15:26.890 --> 01:15:29.650
they're two separate things.

01:15:29.650 --> 01:15:39.770
In general, in my day to day, I haven't really found the big limit of express yet.

01:15:39.770 --> 01:15:47.491
With Shiny core, you do have potentially more flexibility to refactor things.

01:15:47.491 --> 01:15:49.451
But I haven't really...

01:15:49.451 --> 01:15:55.251
Again, personally, I haven't really hit limitations with express building single page dashboards...

01:15:55.251 --> 01:15:56.251
Yet.

01:15:56.251 --> 01:16:00.090
I haven't hit it yet.

01:16:00.090 --> 01:16:05.210
Even in scenarios where I'm going to go through this exercise doing something in express,

01:16:05.210 --> 01:16:06.210
and then it's like...

01:16:06.210 --> 01:16:09.330
Oh, it works with all of this LLM stuff with multi-pages.

01:16:09.330 --> 01:16:10.330
And it's like...

01:16:10.330 --> 01:16:11.330
Okay.

01:16:11.330 --> 01:16:12.330
So it does get you really far.

01:16:12.330 --> 01:16:13.330
The other part of this question is...

01:16:13.330 --> 01:16:14.410
Can you mix the two together?

01:16:14.410 --> 01:16:16.691
The answer to that is no.

01:16:16.890 --> 01:16:23.131
You do have to make an initial decision of express mode or core mode.

01:16:23.131 --> 01:16:26.330
It's in some sense also similar, I would say, to Plotly.

01:16:26.330 --> 01:16:31.371
I believe 90% of you, when you use Plotly, you're using Plotly.express as PX and you're

01:16:31.371 --> 01:16:34.650
just plotting Plotly code that way.

01:16:34.650 --> 01:16:39.290
Very rarely are you using Plotly, the core version.

01:16:39.290 --> 01:16:43.290
Even I've rarely used the Plotly core version for certain things.

01:16:43.290 --> 01:16:44.290
Yes.

01:16:44.290 --> 01:16:45.970
There are two modes available.

01:16:45.970 --> 01:16:48.251
Part of it is also historic.

01:16:48.251 --> 01:16:53.530
Shiny was available as a dashboarding framework in the R community, and they just ported it

01:16:53.530 --> 01:16:56.330
all to Python one-to-one.

01:16:56.330 --> 01:17:00.090
So that's why something like core mode exists.

01:17:00.090 --> 01:17:07.431
And then to reduce the boilerplate and code you have to type in Shiny, they created express

01:17:07.431 --> 01:17:09.811
mode.

01:17:09.811 --> 01:17:16.650
I'll leave that question up so the engineering team can also get a crack on it.

01:17:16.650 --> 01:17:22.811
And yes, it does support Matplotlib and Seaborn and Plotly and Altair.

01:17:22.811 --> 01:17:25.970
Not just Plot9 and ggplot.

01:17:25.970 --> 01:17:26.970
The answer to that is yes.

01:17:26.970 --> 01:17:28.811
I'm just showing it because that's how my brain works.

01:17:28.811 --> 01:17:34.811
My brain does not work in Matplotlib plotting.

01:17:35.811 --> 01:17:39.811
All right.

01:17:39.811 --> 01:17:42.171
Okay.

01:17:42.171 --> 01:17:43.171
Next slide, Beck.

01:17:43.171 --> 01:17:47.270
This one is just me talking at you.

01:17:47.270 --> 01:17:48.931
For a little bit.

01:17:48.931 --> 01:17:54.371
And I wanted to talk about the core thing that makes Shiny special, which is reactivity.

01:17:54.371 --> 01:18:00.210
There's a couple of links to other presentations that have also talked about reactivity.

01:18:00.210 --> 01:18:02.251
Shiny for Python has been around for a while.

01:18:02.251 --> 01:18:06.691
So yes, all of those talks are in 2023.

01:18:06.691 --> 01:18:11.251
They're all still very, very relevant to this particular topic on reactivity.

01:18:11.251 --> 01:18:16.090
I literally actually just took the diagrams you're about to see from Gordon Shotwell's

01:18:16.090 --> 01:18:17.090
talk.

01:18:17.090 --> 01:18:20.371
But we'll talk about how reactivity works.

01:18:20.371 --> 01:18:26.011
And for any of you who have worked with any other plotting framework before, this is the

01:18:26.011 --> 01:18:32.611
part that will be very different with how Shiny goes and figures out how things are

01:18:32.611 --> 01:18:39.970
connected to one another and how things need to be executed or reexecuted.

01:18:39.970 --> 01:18:46.011
So again, reactivity is the key word when you're talking about Shiny.

01:18:46.011 --> 01:18:48.770
It is essentially how it all works.

01:18:48.770 --> 01:18:54.951
And essentially it is a mechanism that allows you to connect the output to an input and

01:18:54.951 --> 01:19:00.111
Shiny goes and figures out how those things are linked to one another.

01:19:00.111 --> 01:19:03.910
The benefit of reactivity is you don't have to write a callback.

01:19:03.910 --> 01:19:11.191
So in Dash, all of your output components, you have to say, like, I need to track what

01:19:11.191 --> 01:19:17.111
the input is so that any time the input changes, it knows that that's what the output is.

01:19:17.111 --> 01:19:21.790
Writing callbacks, if you've written JavaScript apps before, one of the pitfalls is it's a

01:19:21.790 --> 01:19:26.751
lot of manual accounting, which means that you could put an input somewhere and if you

01:19:26.751 --> 01:19:31.991
never explicitly write the callback, those changes you're making aren't updating the

01:19:31.991 --> 01:19:32.991
application.

01:19:32.991 --> 01:19:35.551
Again, it's sort of...

01:19:35.551 --> 01:19:38.470
If you're keeping track of your callbacks, maybe you'll notice that, like, hey, when

01:19:38.470 --> 01:19:43.470
I click on this, the app isn't loading or changing and that's how you catch that you

01:19:43.470 --> 01:19:44.830
didn't write a callback.

01:19:44.830 --> 01:19:48.090
But at the end of the day, Shiny is...

01:19:48.090 --> 01:19:51.150
One of the things that makes Shiny different is you don't have to write a callback.

01:19:51.150 --> 01:19:54.790
The way it handles that process is through reactivity.

01:19:54.790 --> 01:19:56.431
And I think it's pretty intuitive.

01:19:56.431 --> 01:20:00.631
You say input, the name of the ID, parentheses, maybe the parentheses part is a little bit

01:20:00.631 --> 01:20:07.071
weird, but that's how you link the reactive parts together.

01:20:07.071 --> 01:20:09.270
So how does this work?

01:20:09.270 --> 01:20:12.991
Let's say we have a fairly complicated application.

01:20:12.991 --> 01:20:16.150
All of these rectangles are inputs.

01:20:16.150 --> 01:20:20.111
We haven't talked about reactive calculations yet, but you'll see it in the next app example

01:20:20.111 --> 01:20:21.230
that we're building.

01:20:21.230 --> 01:20:23.191
And then we have two outputs.

01:20:23.191 --> 01:20:28.590
One is a model score and the other is some API response.

01:20:28.590 --> 01:20:30.730
So this is the application.

01:20:30.730 --> 01:20:36.830
When you run Shiny, it finds and realizes, hey, you have a whole bunch of stuff in here

01:20:36.830 --> 01:20:40.551
and it just knows about them.

01:20:40.551 --> 01:20:45.150
When the application loads up, it's going to be, hey, what needs to be displayed on

01:20:45.150 --> 01:20:46.150
the page?

01:20:46.150 --> 01:20:47.150
Okay.

01:20:47.150 --> 01:20:49.871
I need to show you whatever this model score is.

01:20:50.631 --> 01:20:52.350
Maybe it's a piece of text that gives you the R squared number.

01:20:52.350 --> 01:20:54.551
Let's just use that as the example here.

01:20:54.551 --> 01:20:59.350
It's a piece of text on the screen and it's like, okay, you told me to show you this piece

01:20:59.350 --> 01:21:00.590
of text.

01:21:00.590 --> 01:21:04.111
That's one of those output components that I talked about.

01:21:04.111 --> 01:21:06.530
In our previous example, it was a plot.

01:21:06.530 --> 01:21:09.470
It could be a data frame table.

01:21:09.470 --> 01:21:12.871
Pretend that this is a piece of a rendered text element.

01:21:12.871 --> 01:21:17.030
So the way this works is it goes and runs that output function.

01:21:17.191 --> 01:21:21.710
In the output function, you saw that it's like input dot something parenthesis.

01:21:21.710 --> 01:21:27.671
When it runs that, it goes, oh, you told me to look up something called filtered.

01:21:27.671 --> 01:21:30.991
Filtered is the name of that ID.

01:21:30.991 --> 01:21:34.131
Filtered is something that is in this case also a function.

01:21:34.131 --> 01:21:38.330
When it goes and calculates, it's going to be like, oh, you told me to go look up this

01:21:38.330 --> 01:21:45.830
input called account and now it knows to look at the account input to see what gets filtered.

01:21:45.830 --> 01:21:49.011
The filtered also depends on a larger data set.

01:21:49.011 --> 01:21:52.431
So it's like, okay, I need the sample and the account.

01:21:52.431 --> 01:21:59.111
But sample, when it runs its code, it's going to see another input call in some sense.

01:21:59.111 --> 01:22:02.551
And then it's going to look up and it's like, okay, in order to get sample, I need dates

01:22:02.551 --> 01:22:03.951
and sample size.

01:22:03.951 --> 01:22:09.191
And so the arrows are drawing in a downward fashion, but it's really looking in reverse

01:22:09.191 --> 01:22:12.970
in how things are calculated.

01:22:12.970 --> 01:22:15.511
So that's how it goes and generates the model score.

01:22:15.511 --> 01:22:17.111
Now it knows how everything is connected.

01:22:17.111 --> 01:22:21.671
It's now going to run everything and then you get your R squared number on your website.

01:22:21.671 --> 01:22:26.470
And then it goes and says, oh, wait, you need this other thing displayed on this page, this

01:22:26.470 --> 01:22:27.470
API response.

01:22:27.470 --> 01:22:28.470
What does it need?

01:22:28.470 --> 01:22:29.470
Okay.

01:22:29.470 --> 01:22:30.470
It runs that function.

01:22:30.470 --> 01:22:31.470
Finds that it needs filtered.

01:22:31.470 --> 01:22:32.931
Filter's already been calculated.

01:22:32.931 --> 01:22:35.751
It's already there.

01:22:35.751 --> 01:22:38.131
Essentially it's already been cached.

01:22:38.131 --> 01:22:41.511
So giving you the API response is really fast.

01:22:41.511 --> 01:22:46.830
It doesn't need to go and work its way all the way back and recalculate everything.

01:22:46.830 --> 01:22:47.830
It's already there.

01:22:47.830 --> 01:22:49.311
So let me just feed it to you.

01:22:49.311 --> 01:22:54.311
So reactivity, one of the other things you get from it is it tries to do the most efficient

01:22:54.311 --> 01:22:55.910
computes.

01:22:55.910 --> 01:22:58.431
Like what needs to get computed or recomputed.

01:22:58.431 --> 01:23:02.631
It tries to figure that out in the most efficient way.

01:23:02.631 --> 01:23:03.931
So that's how reactivity works.

01:23:03.931 --> 01:23:08.111
So if we go through another example of let's say the user changes the account.

01:23:08.111 --> 01:23:12.470
Needs a radio button, a dropdown, piece of text.

01:23:12.470 --> 01:23:17.991
When you go and change one of the inputs, because this diagram, like what you see visually,

01:23:17.991 --> 01:23:23.551
has already been created and being tracked of in Shiny, it's going to say, okay, everything

01:23:23.551 --> 01:23:27.131
downstream of this change is now invalidated.

01:23:27.131 --> 01:23:30.390
So it will go and invalidate everything downstream.

01:23:30.390 --> 01:23:32.790
And then you go back to the same process as before.

01:23:32.790 --> 01:23:34.630
You asked me to show you a piece of text.

01:23:34.630 --> 01:23:36.471
I'm going to run that function.

01:23:36.471 --> 01:23:38.191
It depends on filtered.

01:23:38.191 --> 01:23:39.591
Filtered needs to get recalculated.

01:23:39.591 --> 01:23:40.591
Okay.

01:23:40.591 --> 01:23:41.591
The account number changed.

01:23:41.591 --> 01:23:44.510
So that's how you get a new filtered data set.

01:23:44.510 --> 01:23:48.471
But the sample didn't change, because those inputs didn't change.

01:23:48.471 --> 01:23:51.711
So we can still use the old cache value of sample.

01:23:51.711 --> 01:23:54.231
So we don't have to recompute that, right?

01:23:54.231 --> 01:23:59.231
You can take this idea to the extreme of like if each one of these steps took 10 seconds,

01:23:59.231 --> 01:24:04.750
changing account only caused a 10 second change instead of a 30 second change.

01:24:04.750 --> 01:24:10.711
And then because filtered change, it invalidated the API response, you also told me to show

01:24:10.711 --> 01:24:13.091
you the API response on the site.

01:24:13.091 --> 01:24:15.990
It's going to go and be like, okay, filter's already been calculated.

01:24:15.990 --> 01:24:19.711
Let me just give you that cache result again.

01:24:19.711 --> 01:24:22.990
So now if we go through the example, like what happens if sample size change?

01:24:22.990 --> 01:24:24.671
So it goes through the same process.

01:24:24.671 --> 01:24:27.551
Everything downstream now gets invalidated.

01:24:27.551 --> 01:24:30.510
So now everything is blank.

01:24:30.510 --> 01:24:33.390
And then you're back to your initial state.

01:24:33.390 --> 01:24:36.510
And it says, what needs to be drawn on the screen?

01:24:36.510 --> 01:24:40.270
And you go back through that very first example again, right?

01:24:40.270 --> 01:24:47.671
So just by saying input.id parentheses, that's all it takes from you as the end user to keep

01:24:47.671 --> 01:24:49.150
track of this graph.

01:24:49.150 --> 01:24:53.790
You don't need to, again, write a callback, because all of these arrows essentially is

01:24:53.790 --> 01:24:59.311
what you have to do, depending on the framework you're working with, like when you hear callback,

01:24:59.311 --> 01:25:00.870
you have to keep track of all of this.

01:25:00.870 --> 01:25:03.990
You have to write it in your actual code.

01:25:03.990 --> 01:25:10.071
In Shiny, I have this thing, I need it right now, and you just let the graph figure itself

01:25:10.071 --> 01:25:13.191
out.

01:25:13.191 --> 01:25:15.471
So that's the really cool thing about it.

01:25:15.471 --> 01:25:19.790
You never really have to worry about, oh, I never connected dates properly.

01:25:19.790 --> 01:25:24.431
As long as you're using the date input, it's up to you, if you mess that up, like you never

01:25:24.431 --> 01:25:29.390
used it and you're still using the hard-coded date, which I've done in the past, yes, that

01:25:29.390 --> 01:25:31.110
is a mistake.

01:25:31.110 --> 01:25:35.831
But you don't have to keep track of, like, let's say you're thinking dates, this input

01:25:35.831 --> 01:25:38.231
was being used in like five other places.

01:25:38.231 --> 01:25:41.110
You don't have to keep track of that anywhere.

01:25:41.110 --> 01:25:47.910
You just go and use the thing, and the reactive framework will go and calculate that for you.

01:25:47.910 --> 01:25:54.110
And it will go and figure out what is the minimum amount of extra computations or executions

01:25:54.110 --> 01:25:56.270
it needs.

01:25:56.270 --> 01:25:58.071
So that's how Shiny works.

01:25:58.071 --> 01:26:04.951
By magic of input.paren, that's kind of what you need.

01:26:04.951 --> 01:26:06.431
Which is kind of cool.

01:26:06.431 --> 01:26:07.431
All right.

