I'll take any volunteer.

01:26:42.510 --> 01:26:45.510
What do you see?

01:26:45.510 --> 01:26:50.030
You can call out an input, you can call out an output, you can call out a visual component,

01:26:50.030 --> 01:26:51.030
if you want.

01:26:51.030 --> 01:26:52.030
Slider.

01:26:52.030 --> 01:26:53.030
Yes, yes.

01:26:53.030 --> 01:27:03.351
I'm also a university teacher, I'm okay with just standing here until someone says something.

01:27:03.351 --> 01:27:04.351
But yes.

01:27:04.351 --> 01:27:05.510
You have a slider.

01:27:05.510 --> 01:27:07.951
That is on the left-hand side.

01:27:07.951 --> 01:27:11.671
One of the other things that's really hard to tell, also the fact that this is a static

01:27:11.671 --> 01:27:14.150
image, is there's a little arrow here.

01:27:14.150 --> 01:27:19.551
And so these inputs are actually on a collapsible sidebar as well.

01:27:20.270 --> 01:27:25.551
I don't, since the internet for that site isn't working, and I'm not gonna want to wait

01:27:25.551 --> 01:27:31.071
for the site, there's another part in that dropdown on the site that said components.

01:27:31.071 --> 01:27:35.351
There's another page that says layouts and layouts.

01:27:35.351 --> 01:27:38.770
A sidebar is a particular type of layout.

01:27:38.770 --> 01:27:45.311
So you can get the boilerplate code on how to make this little sidebar thing go away.

01:27:45.311 --> 01:27:51.551
Each one of these things are cards or value boxes, so we can have really important metrics

01:27:51.551 --> 01:27:56.910
sort of take up a little bit more space, have a nice little bounding box around it to give

01:27:56.910 --> 01:28:00.510
it a little bit more visual distinction.

01:28:00.510 --> 01:28:04.071
And we can put information in here, or actual icons.

01:28:04.071 --> 01:28:08.711
So these are really good for those big top-level metrics that you're interested in.

01:28:08.711 --> 01:28:12.870
In this particular example, all of these are going to be different types of output.

01:28:12.870 --> 01:28:16.790
This is going to be dependent on a render text output, because when the sliders change,

01:28:16.790 --> 01:28:18.270
I expect the numbers to change.

01:28:18.270 --> 01:28:23.150
So it's going to be render text, compared to before, which is render plot.

01:28:23.150 --> 01:28:25.030
So this right here, this was also another question.

01:28:25.030 --> 01:28:27.510
This is render data frame.

01:28:27.510 --> 01:28:32.110
And the other question is, yes, I believe Shiny works with NOR walls, which means like

01:28:32.110 --> 01:28:39.071
you can put in any data frame-like object, and Shiny will be able to render it in here.

01:28:39.071 --> 01:28:47.750
Your Python code itself can handle Polar's code, for example, and Shiny will do the Polar's

01:28:47.750 --> 01:28:48.750
thing.

01:28:48.750 --> 01:28:52.150
And if you need to display the data frame or the data, it's right here.

01:28:52.150 --> 01:28:57.870
Or if you just need the output from Polar's, then you have a little calculation box there.

01:28:57.870 --> 01:28:58.870
We'll work with Plotly.

01:28:58.870 --> 01:29:00.870
So here's a little Plotly figure.

01:29:00.870 --> 01:29:05.071
So instead of a static figure, this is a more interactive figure.

01:29:05.071 --> 01:29:09.471
This is using the IPyWidget system to get this into Shiny.

01:29:09.471 --> 01:29:15.671
So all of those other features with maps or interactive plots, you can do that with Shiny.

01:29:15.671 --> 01:29:21.510
And then down here is a visualization that is built on top of Plotly called RidgePlot.

01:29:21.510 --> 01:29:27.471
So you can have some other plotting library object down here as well.

01:29:27.471 --> 01:29:32.431
The trick is, you may need to know where this thing is coming from.

01:29:32.431 --> 01:29:36.831
So looking at the RidgePlot documentation, I think they said something like, yeah, it's

01:29:36.831 --> 01:29:37.831
a Plotly thing.

01:29:37.831 --> 01:29:41.390
So OK, we know it's a Plotly thing.

01:29:41.390 --> 01:29:46.711
Once you know it's a Plotly thing, you know it's an IPyWidget thing, and then OK, at render

01:29:46.711 --> 01:29:50.870
IPyWidget, and essentially that's what's going to happen.

01:29:50.870 --> 01:29:53.851
So let's talk about all the different parts on this page.

01:29:53.851 --> 01:29:56.910
You have actually a title, which I also totally forgot.

