02:26:37.369 --> 02:26:43.130
So we are going to first talk about the anatomy of a conversation.

02:26:43.130 --> 02:26:50.650
How does a conversation between us and a chatbot actually work?

02:26:50.650 --> 02:26:51.650
Each...

02:26:51.650 --> 02:26:58.010
A conversation is really a sequence of HTTP requests.

02:26:58.010 --> 02:26:59.690
There's a server.

02:26:59.690 --> 02:27:01.890
And it is entirely stateless.

02:27:01.890 --> 02:27:02.890
That is a keyword.

02:27:02.890 --> 02:27:03.890
And I'll show you...

02:27:03.890 --> 02:27:07.289
I'll talk to you about the ramifications from that in a little bit.

02:27:07.289 --> 02:27:10.130
But you talk to a server, and it gives you back a response.

02:27:10.130 --> 02:27:13.249
And then you re-ask another question, and you talk to a server, and it gives you back

02:27:13.249 --> 02:27:14.249
another response.

02:27:14.249 --> 02:27:19.390
And it's entirely stateless in that the server, like, when you make the second request, technically

02:27:19.390 --> 02:27:26.249
doesn't know that you had a previous, like, line of conversation with it.

02:27:26.249 --> 02:27:27.929
Which is not how we interact.

02:27:27.929 --> 02:27:28.929
As humans.

02:27:28.929 --> 02:27:34.489
But it is actually how it interacts with the LLM, even though it seems like it somehow

02:27:34.489 --> 02:27:35.890
remembers stuff.

02:27:35.890 --> 02:27:39.690
But at the end of the day, everything is an HTTP request.

02:27:39.690 --> 02:27:47.010
And the server that you're talking to, whether it's OpenAI or Anthropic or Google, is entirely

02:27:47.010 --> 02:27:48.570
stateless.

02:27:48.570 --> 02:27:51.049
So if we have a conversation and we say...

02:27:51.049 --> 02:27:53.450
What is the capital of the moon?

02:27:53.450 --> 02:27:54.450
You get a response.

02:27:54.450 --> 02:27:55.450
There isn't one.

02:27:55.970 --> 02:27:56.970
And if you say...

02:27:56.970 --> 02:27:59.289
Are you sure?

02:27:59.289 --> 02:28:00.729
The response will be something like...

02:28:00.729 --> 02:28:01.729
Yes, I'm sure.

02:28:01.729 --> 02:28:02.729
Right?

02:28:02.729 --> 02:28:03.729
And like...

02:28:03.729 --> 02:28:07.409
This seems like there's this concept of memory.

02:28:07.409 --> 02:28:08.409
But I just said...

02:28:08.409 --> 02:28:09.409
It's stateless.

02:28:09.409 --> 02:28:11.770
There's actually no concept of memory going on.

02:28:11.770 --> 02:28:17.929
So in the HTTP request, the way this works is...

02:28:17.929 --> 02:28:19.609
You have some role.

02:28:19.609 --> 02:28:20.929
There's a system prompt.

02:28:20.929 --> 02:28:21.929
Right?

02:28:21.929 --> 02:28:26.609
And this is a prompt that a lot of people talk about that is specific to DLLM.

02:28:26.609 --> 02:28:31.609
And you don't necessarily, when you're talking with it, have the ability to change it.

02:28:31.609 --> 02:28:35.489
But then you are able to ask a question.

02:28:35.489 --> 02:28:37.929
What is the capital of the moon?

02:28:37.929 --> 02:28:40.369
And you'll notice that this comes from the actual user.

02:28:40.369 --> 02:28:47.809
So it's able to keep track of who is saying what, what the rules are, what the model you

02:28:47.809 --> 02:28:52.929
have is, and then your API key or stuff like that.

02:28:52.929 --> 02:28:54.609
So you can specify the model.

02:28:54.609 --> 02:28:55.609
Here's the components.

02:28:55.609 --> 02:28:57.470
And there we go.

02:28:57.470 --> 02:28:59.890
And then you get a response back.

02:28:59.890 --> 02:29:01.369
The response, you'll have...

02:29:01.369 --> 02:29:03.530
There's a specific type of role called assistant.

02:29:03.530 --> 02:29:04.530
And it'll be like...

02:29:04.530 --> 02:29:05.530
The moon doesn't have a capital.

02:29:05.530 --> 02:29:08.510
And that's the answer that you actually get back.

02:29:08.510 --> 02:29:10.770
Other things that you'll say is...

02:29:10.770 --> 02:29:13.409
Why did the answer stop?

02:29:13.409 --> 02:29:14.409
It's because...

02:29:14.409 --> 02:29:15.409
Well, it just stopped.

02:29:15.409 --> 02:29:16.409
That's it.

02:29:16.409 --> 02:29:17.450
One of the reasons why it would stop is...

02:29:17.450 --> 02:29:19.210
You ran out of money.

02:29:19.210 --> 02:29:20.390
And I ran out of tokens.

02:29:20.390 --> 02:29:24.169
So if you want me to give you more words, give me more money is sort of another type

02:29:24.169 --> 02:29:25.770
of reason.

02:29:25.770 --> 02:29:26.770
Other things...

02:29:26.770 --> 02:29:31.169
LLMs are highly dependent on what's known as a token.

02:29:31.169 --> 02:29:33.729
It's almost like a word.

02:29:33.729 --> 02:29:39.530
And essentially you're paying for the number of token transactions.

02:29:39.530 --> 02:29:41.450
And so...

02:29:41.450 --> 02:29:44.890
When you go and ask a follow-up question...

02:29:44.890 --> 02:29:45.890
How does the moon...

02:29:45.890 --> 02:29:46.890
Like...

02:29:46.890 --> 02:29:47.890
The assistant goes like...

02:29:47.890 --> 02:29:49.330
No, it doesn't really have a thing.

02:29:49.330 --> 02:29:50.330
And you say...

02:29:50.330 --> 02:29:51.330
Are you sure?

02:29:51.330 --> 02:29:53.249
You'll notice that when you type in all you...

02:29:53.249 --> 02:29:56.770
Are you sure?

02:29:56.770 --> 02:29:57.770
This is the entire payload.

02:29:57.770 --> 02:30:01.409
Like, the conversation history actually went with it.

02:30:01.409 --> 02:30:03.370
And what that means is...

02:30:03.370 --> 02:30:05.730
If you actually look at the response and it's like...

02:30:05.730 --> 02:30:06.730
The assistant is this.

02:30:06.730 --> 02:30:08.529
And you look at the number of tokens.

02:30:08.529 --> 02:30:12.889
It went from a really small number to a fairly large number.

02:30:12.889 --> 02:30:16.090
And it doesn't seem like it made...

02:30:16.090 --> 02:30:20.330
Clearly that number jumped higher than what you would expect if it was remembering stuff

02:30:20.330 --> 02:30:21.330
along the way.

02:30:21.330 --> 02:30:24.690
And it's because when you go ask the follow-up question, literally all the history went with

02:30:24.690 --> 02:30:25.690
the follow-up question.

02:30:25.690 --> 02:30:26.690
That's why the token number sort of...

02:30:26.690 --> 02:30:29.090
I don't know if it's exponential growth.

02:30:29.090 --> 02:30:34.090
But it grows the longer and longer you have your conversation.

02:30:34.090 --> 02:30:37.210
And that's in general how all LLMs work.

02:30:37.210 --> 02:30:40.529
There's techniques that people are coming up with that try to cache things.

02:30:40.529 --> 02:30:45.289
But as far as this class goes, that's how it works.

02:30:45.289 --> 02:30:46.850
Which is kind of scary.

02:30:46.850 --> 02:30:52.090
You're going from 12 and you ask the follow-up question, and it went from 67 and you're like...

02:30:52.090 --> 02:30:55.090
That doesn't make sense.

02:30:55.090 --> 02:30:56.809
It's a literal scam.

02:30:56.809 --> 02:30:57.809
That's what's happening.

02:30:57.809 --> 02:30:58.809
So...

02:30:58.809 --> 02:30:59.809
Tokens.

02:30:59.809 --> 02:31:03.409
The fundamental unit of pricing and how things work are on tokens.

02:31:03.409 --> 02:31:04.409
So for example...

02:31:04.409 --> 02:31:05.929
What is the capital of the moon?

02:31:05.929 --> 02:31:10.370
It gets broken up into a sequence of numbers, which represent a token.

02:31:10.370 --> 02:31:12.690
Internally it's all doing math.

02:31:12.690 --> 02:31:14.490
Like transformer math.

02:31:14.490 --> 02:31:17.450
So that's eight pieces of tokens.

02:31:17.450 --> 02:31:21.889
Other words, like counter-revolutionary, will get broken up into four tokens.

02:31:21.889 --> 02:31:24.330
And then you're being paid on that.

