or you're doing something with the context window, which is what RAG is trying to do.

02:50:37.739 --> 02:50:38.739
But that's it.

02:50:38.739 --> 02:50:42.818
There's only a couple places you can ever tweak or fiddle with a chat application.

02:50:42.818 --> 02:50:47.778
So if you get a little bit overwhelmed with all of the cool features or the hype of what's

02:50:47.778 --> 02:50:50.778
going on, just remember, everything's stateless.

02:50:50.778 --> 02:50:53.938
There's only a couple places that people really have access to tweak.

02:50:53.938 --> 02:50:56.859
And that's really the crux of it all.

02:50:56.859 --> 02:51:03.579
So on top of shiny chat, which is a general, like, you have a conversation with it, what

02:51:03.579 --> 02:51:10.139
we've done is we've modified the system prompt such that it works better with data.

02:51:10.139 --> 02:51:14.698
And what query chat actually does is you feed it a data frame, and it will go column by

02:51:14.698 --> 02:51:20.139
column, figure out the data type of the column, and create essentially, like, the schema of

02:51:20.139 --> 02:51:21.378
your data frame.

02:51:21.378 --> 02:51:26.818
And then all of that information gets put into the system prompt.

02:51:26.818 --> 02:51:27.859
So that's step one.

02:51:27.859 --> 02:51:32.698
Your chat bot now knows some information about your data.

02:51:32.698 --> 02:51:34.619
Whether or not this is a categorical variable.

02:51:34.619 --> 02:51:38.938
If it's categorical, and there's, I think, like, by default, there's less than ten unique

02:51:38.938 --> 02:51:39.938
observations.

02:51:39.938 --> 02:51:43.339
Yes, the bot will know about all ten unique observations.

02:51:43.339 --> 02:51:45.859
But if it's more, it'll treat it like a string.

02:51:45.859 --> 02:51:50.019
If it's a number, it'll know, like, is it an integer or a float?

02:51:50.019 --> 02:51:51.899
And then know the upper and lower bounds of it.

02:51:51.899 --> 02:51:55.899
So that's the information that the chat bot has access to.

02:51:55.938 --> 02:52:00.498
The other thing that makes query chat really different is in the system prompt, we then

02:52:00.498 --> 02:52:05.299
say the only thing that you are able to give back to us is SQL.

02:52:05.299 --> 02:52:06.299
Like, you have to...

02:52:06.299 --> 02:52:12.818
Any time we ask you to say, like, filter my dataset, you have to give me the SQL command

02:52:12.818 --> 02:52:14.859
that tells me how to filter that dataset.

02:52:14.859 --> 02:52:18.498
Or if you need to do some calculation, SQL is pretty powerful.

02:52:18.498 --> 02:52:24.498
You can actually ask it for, like, calculate outliers by using, like, three times the IQR.

02:52:24.778 --> 02:52:27.658
There is an actual IQR function in SQL.

02:52:27.658 --> 02:52:34.419
And so you can get really far with just limiting its response to just SQL.

02:52:34.419 --> 02:52:36.538
And that's essentially what query chat is doing.

02:52:36.538 --> 02:52:41.139
Is instead of that little side panel that opens and closes and you put in a filter,

02:52:41.139 --> 02:52:47.419
a slider, a checkbox, or all of that, if you replace it with a chat bot and you tell this

02:52:47.419 --> 02:52:53.859
chat bot the only thing you can do is speak in SQL, essentially I can take that SQL statement

02:52:53.938 --> 02:53:00.818
and through DuckDB or through Pandas or through Norwals run SQL against it, just like that

02:53:00.818 --> 02:53:03.459
TIPS dashboard that we just had.

02:53:03.459 --> 02:53:05.758
Everything reacted to that one data frame.

02:53:05.758 --> 02:53:10.818
So once SQL is able to filter the data frame, the entire application can filter.

02:53:10.818 --> 02:53:12.179
And that's really cool.

02:53:12.179 --> 02:53:20.019
Because you give the user all the flexibility to specify how they want to filter a dataset

02:53:20.019 --> 02:53:21.899
through natural language.

02:53:21.938 --> 02:53:26.218
And it also frees you as the developer of, like, what happens if you have 50 columns?

02:53:26.218 --> 02:53:29.818
Are you going to put in 50, like, sliders in there?

02:53:29.818 --> 02:53:31.258
That looks really bad.

02:53:31.258 --> 02:53:32.859
I've tried it.

02:53:32.859 --> 02:53:33.859
It looks pretty bad.

02:53:33.859 --> 02:53:35.538
It never looks really good.

02:53:35.538 --> 02:53:42.459
The other thing is you saw it even in the example code with the TIPS dataset, the dashboard

02:53:42.459 --> 02:53:47.938
was if I had two different filters and I wanted to filter the dataset, it was an and operator.

02:53:47.938 --> 02:53:51.059
It's either, like, all of this range or only this.

02:53:51.059 --> 02:53:57.658
There's no way to say any more complex type of logic.

02:53:57.658 --> 02:54:01.339
But if you're specifying in natural language, you can totally do that.

02:54:01.339 --> 02:54:05.019
You can say give me the top ten and you don't have to figure out what the range is for top

02:54:05.019 --> 02:54:06.019
ten.

02:54:06.019 --> 02:54:07.019
Right?

02:54:07.019 --> 02:54:11.139
SQL can go and figure out, like, calculate the percentage, give you the top ten results.

02:54:11.139 --> 02:54:12.139
Right?

02:54:12.139 --> 02:54:13.139
Like, limit ten.

02:54:13.139 --> 02:54:14.139
That's how you get the top ten.

02:54:14.139 --> 02:54:15.139
Right?

02:54:15.139 --> 02:54:18.258
So you now have this ability to, like, yeah, all of those controls that we just talked

02:54:18.258 --> 02:54:23.538
about for the first two hours can in theory be replaced with a chat bot and then you constrain

02:54:23.538 --> 02:54:28.899
it to only speak in SQL given this data schema that you have.

