03:07:34.579 --> 03:07:43.179
If many of you aren't actively creating Shiny for Python applications, but there's a concept

03:07:43.179 --> 03:07:50.099
of a Shiny module that really helps with scaling your application if you have a lot of components

03:07:50.099 --> 03:07:55.219
and you want to section off all of this logic with all of these reactive calcs.

03:07:55.219 --> 03:08:00.858
I just needed to kind of hide it away because it's all tied together, and maybe you have

03:08:00.858 --> 03:08:06.658
a multi-page app and you want each page to be in its own little world and reduce the

03:08:06.658 --> 03:08:09.778
clutter on any individual file.

03:08:09.778 --> 03:08:16.858
So there's this concept of similar to a Python module, which is a .py file that you import,

03:08:16.858 --> 03:08:23.618
there is a concept of a Shiny module, which can be a file that you import, but is really

03:08:23.618 --> 03:08:34.378
a way where you can hide away bits and pieces of Shiny code or reuse different components

03:08:34.378 --> 03:08:36.319
over and over again.

03:08:36.319 --> 03:08:42.059
What is a component that you might, or something that you create that's reused over and over

03:08:42.059 --> 03:08:43.059
again?

03:08:43.059 --> 03:08:50.419
A few weeks ago, I created, with my master students, we had this project where we were

03:08:50.419 --> 03:08:56.579
working with different farms, and we were trying to measure the productivity, how much

03:08:56.579 --> 03:08:59.738
energy and the productivity a farm is able to provide.

03:08:59.738 --> 03:09:04.898
And we worked with one of the research labs at the University of British Columbia where

03:09:04.898 --> 03:09:08.898
we were saying, hey, we care about these metrics, and here are the figures.

03:09:08.898 --> 03:09:13.459
But we had multiple farms to compare, so I had this idea of what if we treat each farm

03:09:13.459 --> 03:09:19.498
like a product of the Apple website, where you can compare your laptops together, give

03:09:19.498 --> 03:09:24.459
you the option to pick a dropdown and compare multiple farms with one another.

03:09:24.459 --> 03:09:28.258
And that was a really fun idea, because you can look across, and you'll see the same figure

03:09:28.258 --> 03:09:31.939
or the same number across multiple farms.

03:09:31.939 --> 03:09:37.378
But I also wanted the ability to have that, like, compare field, where you can click on

03:09:37.378 --> 03:09:42.059
a button, and it will let you, it will create another column, and you can do another dropdown

03:09:42.059 --> 03:09:43.898
to pick another farm.

03:09:43.898 --> 03:09:49.258
So just like you can select three or five different Apple products that you can compare,

03:09:49.258 --> 03:09:54.059
you can select three or five different columns and then make a dropdown.

03:09:54.059 --> 03:10:00.258
And so that was a really good example of a shiny module case, because one column is just

03:10:00.258 --> 03:10:02.059
being repeated over and over again.

03:10:02.059 --> 03:10:07.738
But the most important thing that I'll bring up again that we mentioned in the first hour

03:10:07.738 --> 03:10:12.278
was, like, the idea of each component is really important.

03:10:12.278 --> 03:10:16.939
The other thing I didn't mention is the idea of each component has to be unique.

03:10:16.939 --> 03:10:22.858
So I can't just, like, write a function that just pops in another, like, all of that data

03:10:22.858 --> 03:10:26.339
again, because the ID is not going to be unique.

03:10:26.339 --> 03:10:30.538
So you need a mechanism to change the ID of something.

03:10:30.538 --> 03:10:33.898
And that has to be tied to all of the output components, because you're reading it from

03:10:33.898 --> 03:10:40.419
the ID, and there's this tight coupling of inputs and outputs and the name of the ID.

03:10:40.419 --> 03:10:46.099
This is the problem that shiny modules tries to solve, and this is how you can scale applications,

03:10:46.258 --> 03:10:53.138
especially if there's a component or a part of the application that needs to get repeated.

03:10:53.138 --> 03:10:59.579
So here's another motivation of less of something that gets repeated, but you might have an

03:10:59.579 --> 03:11:04.018
application that just has a whole bunch of different parts, and you just want to segment

03:11:04.018 --> 03:11:07.018
off these parts away from your app.

03:11:07.018 --> 03:11:12.299
Modules are another way to sort of just, hey, this is all, like, related to one another.

03:11:12.299 --> 03:11:14.018
All of these reactive calcs, they're all together.

03:11:14.018 --> 03:11:20.299
They don't really get used anywhere else, but I have a 3,000, 5,000 line dashboard file,

03:11:20.299 --> 03:11:22.618
and this is just really hard to maintain.

03:11:22.618 --> 03:11:27.579
How do I sort of break these things apart such that, you know, maybe the data part is

03:11:27.579 --> 03:11:31.179
in its own little, like, shiny module?

03:11:31.179 --> 03:11:36.179
So you can also use modules as a way to help scale your application, which is technically

03:11:36.179 --> 03:11:40.518
part of the title of this workshop that we're getting to right now.

03:11:40.518 --> 03:11:43.518
So here is an example of an application.

03:11:43.518 --> 03:11:49.799
And I believe this works.

03:11:49.799 --> 03:11:51.158
Yep.

03:11:51.158 --> 03:11:55.998
So nothing too fancy.

03:11:55.998 --> 03:11:56.998
But it is...

03:11:56.998 --> 03:11:57.998
It's got a few...

03:11:57.998 --> 03:11:58.998
Oh, no.

03:11:58.998 --> 03:11:59.998
Give me one second.

03:11:59.998 --> 03:12:02.998
Okay.

03:12:02.998 --> 03:12:05.998
So...

03:12:05.998 --> 03:12:08.998
Uh-oh.

03:12:08.998 --> 03:12:19.998
Do you see?

03:12:19.998 --> 03:12:24.278
Okay.

03:12:24.278 --> 03:12:29.278
So, again, it's not the perfect example of why we want to use modules, but we'll sort

03:12:29.278 --> 03:12:36.358
of break this part apart, this application, such that we'll convert this code into a module.

03:12:36.358 --> 03:12:40.278
And what is the thing that we want all tied together is these three filters with this

03:12:40.278 --> 03:12:41.278
particular dataset.

03:12:41.278 --> 03:12:48.199
And that's something that we want traveling together in modular form.

03:12:48.199 --> 03:12:50.158
So here's our initial app.

03:12:50.158 --> 03:12:51.839
What does this app look like?

03:12:51.839 --> 03:12:55.919
So it looks like we have this input checkbox group.

03:12:55.919 --> 03:12:57.278
We have an input slider.

03:12:57.278 --> 03:12:59.079
We have an input slider.

03:12:59.079 --> 03:13:06.118
And those are the inputs of this particular application.

03:13:06.118 --> 03:13:11.679
One of the things about this particular slide deck is I wrote all of this code in Shiny

03:13:11.679 --> 03:13:12.679
Core.

03:13:12.679 --> 03:13:15.238
So you'll have a glimpse of what Shiny Core looks like.

03:13:15.238 --> 03:13:21.398
Essentially, instead of just using width statements and just calling UI.input checkbox

03:13:21.398 --> 03:13:28.959
group, I'm saving all of these into a particular variable that contains all of the UI components.

03:13:28.959 --> 03:13:33.679
So it's a little bit more code, because I have to wrap everything in a UI component

03:13:33.679 --> 03:13:35.959
variable or a UI variable.

03:13:35.959 --> 03:13:39.878
But everything that I just showed you with Shiny Express is the same.

03:13:39.878 --> 03:13:42.199
Here's the thing I wanted to show up here.

03:13:42.199 --> 03:13:44.959
This is where it shows up.

03:13:44.959 --> 03:13:47.998
Modules aren't just tied to Shiny Core.

03:13:47.998 --> 03:13:50.799
You can use modules for Shiny Express.

03:13:50.799 --> 03:13:57.118
I just sort of said, hey, I'm not asking you to copy or run this code.

03:13:57.118 --> 03:13:59.358
So it's okay.

03:13:59.358 --> 03:14:04.358
So in the server code, we've seen a reactive calc.

03:14:04.358 --> 03:14:06.118
In this reactive calc, it's really similar.

03:14:06.118 --> 03:14:10.199
We have some type of variable that will handle a mask.

03:14:10.199 --> 03:14:12.358
We will go apply each of the filters.

03:14:12.358 --> 03:14:19.599
So this is my original way of find all of the...

03:14:19.599 --> 03:14:22.839
Apply the filters for each of the columns.

03:14:22.839 --> 03:14:25.238
If it's a number, do that.

03:14:25.238 --> 03:14:28.358
Otherwise, if it's a categorical, do some other stuff.

03:14:28.358 --> 03:14:31.799
And then at the end of the day, just return my filter data frame and then show it.

03:14:31.799 --> 03:14:39.719
So multiple ways where you can say, take in all of the components of the input and then

03:14:39.719 --> 03:14:43.538
apply those filters to our data frame.

03:14:43.538 --> 03:14:56.398
So one of the ways that we can do it is write a for loop to create all of the UI elements.

03:14:56.398 --> 03:14:58.919
So what are we trying to do right now?

03:14:58.919 --> 03:15:12.799
What we're trying to do is for each of the columns in my data frame...

03:15:12.799 --> 03:15:18.179
For each of the columns in my data frame, if it's a number, I want you to create a slider.

03:15:18.179 --> 03:15:23.398
If it's a categorical variable, I want you to go and create a checkbox group.

03:15:23.398 --> 03:15:27.839
And so one way that you can do it is I have a list of things.

03:15:27.839 --> 03:15:32.679
I want you to iterate through this list and then go and create that list from it.

03:15:32.679 --> 03:15:37.758
So I've sectioned off the most important parts is, hey, I have all of my filters.

03:15:37.758 --> 03:15:40.518
And I'm gonna go through each one of my columns.

03:15:40.518 --> 03:15:45.959
And I'm going to look at the type of that particular column.

03:15:45.959 --> 03:15:48.038
And if it's a number, return a slider.

03:15:48.038 --> 03:15:51.998
If it's not a number, return a checkbox group.

03:15:51.998 --> 03:15:56.358
And one of the things you'll also see is I am setting the filter...

03:15:56.358 --> 03:15:58.878
The ID to be filter underscore column name.

03:15:58.878 --> 03:16:05.278
And it's my kind of way of saying I'm assuming that each of the variable names or the columns

03:16:05.278 --> 03:16:09.278
in my dataset are going to be unique and I don't have two of the same column names.

03:16:09.278 --> 03:16:17.998
And I'm going to use that as the ID of my UI component.

03:16:17.998 --> 03:16:22.118
But what happens if we need to track more information?

03:16:22.118 --> 03:16:27.319
Which is...

03:16:27.319 --> 03:16:36.158
We need to also track the kind of filter, not just if it's a number, make it a slider.

03:16:36.158 --> 03:16:41.398
So for example, what happens if I need to know...

03:16:41.398 --> 03:16:46.638
No, I really want this to be a two-way slider, because that's the range that I'm going for.

03:16:47.038 --> 03:16:49.559
This only makes sense if it's an individual number.

03:16:49.559 --> 03:16:55.638
So now I'm trying to track not just the column name, which then feeds into the ID.

03:16:55.638 --> 03:17:02.038
I now need to track some other variable that is like a piece of metadata on that column.

03:17:02.038 --> 03:17:04.079
And so you can do that.

03:17:04.079 --> 03:17:09.158
You can sort of write it out as a list comprehension, and then now you have all of the pieces of

03:17:09.158 --> 03:17:16.758
information sort of traveling together one at a time to go in and reactively or dynamically

03:17:16.758 --> 03:17:21.238
create the inputs that you need.

03:17:21.238 --> 03:17:25.959
So when you need to do something like that, what you need to do is...

03:17:25.959 --> 03:17:32.118
This is a part that we didn't really talk about today until now, which is you can actually

03:17:32.118 --> 03:17:39.799
write code that generates user inputs, and then use that dynamically generated user

03:17:39.799 --> 03:17:42.158
input as the actual input in your code.

03:17:42.158 --> 03:17:46.959
It's kind of meta in that sense, where instead of saying, like, I want a checkbox right here,

03:17:46.959 --> 03:17:52.919
and checkbox shows up, you can actually write some type of reactive code that says...

03:17:52.919 --> 03:17:55.038
If this happens, put in a checkbox.

03:17:55.038 --> 03:17:57.278
If that happens, put in a slider.

03:17:57.278 --> 03:18:06.238
And use that return object as something that shows up as the input component in your application.

03:18:06.238 --> 03:18:13.319
So in Shiny Express, anything that was like an at render is essentially server code.

03:18:13.319 --> 03:18:17.719
So you can actually say, like, hey, I want to generate a piece of UI.

03:18:17.719 --> 03:18:19.878
That's what gets reactively generated.

03:18:19.878 --> 03:18:22.278
And then I just want you to put that right there.

03:18:22.278 --> 03:18:24.799
So you can also do that in Shiny as well.

03:18:25.319 --> 03:18:29.238
Again, that example, we didn't really cover in our tips or our Penguins example.

03:18:29.238 --> 03:18:31.878
But that is another really good use case where...

03:18:31.878 --> 03:18:37.319
Yeah, like, if you're asking a user to upload a data frame, you probably want different

03:18:37.319 --> 03:18:40.878
things showing up on the screen, depending on...

03:18:40.878 --> 03:18:43.439
You know, if you're working with...

03:18:43.439 --> 03:18:46.479
You know, maybe they submit a, like...

03:18:46.479 --> 03:18:47.479
What's a good example?

03:18:47.479 --> 03:18:51.919
I don't have a good example off the top of my head.

03:18:51.919 --> 03:18:59.719
What happens if your dashboard accepts, like, two different types of, like, machine-generated

03:18:59.719 --> 03:19:00.719
output?

03:19:00.719 --> 03:19:03.158
And one is from machine A and one is from machine B?

03:19:03.158 --> 03:19:07.378
You can go and figure out what data set is coming from what machine.

03:19:07.378 --> 03:19:10.638
Maybe it's that simple as counting the number of rows.

03:19:10.638 --> 03:19:13.358
And then that governs, like, the entire how...

03:19:13.358 --> 03:19:15.959
What application layout gets loaded.

03:19:15.959 --> 03:19:21.079
So that is something that you can do with this render UI component is, hey, when I get

03:19:21.238 --> 03:19:25.919
this output, render all of this other stuff in one way versus another.

03:19:25.919 --> 03:19:26.919
So...

03:19:22.634 --> 03:19:26.474
So, there's a couple ways that we can, you know,

03:19:26.474 --> 03:19:31.154
when we are trying to create a whole bunch of UI elements,

03:19:31.154 --> 03:19:33.434
you can use a for loop to create the input components.

03:19:33.434 --> 03:19:37.034
You can use a for loop to read the input components.

03:19:37.034 --> 03:19:38.553
You can see, you can use a for loop

03:19:38.553 --> 03:19:41.354
to place the input components somewhere.

03:19:41.354 --> 03:19:43.914
You could define a helper function

03:19:43.914 --> 03:19:47.194
that essentially uses a for loop to put stuff there,

03:19:47.194 --> 03:19:48.834
or you could dynamically render it

03:19:48.834 --> 03:19:50.994
with something like render.ui.

03:19:50.994 --> 03:19:55.353
But, and in our particular use case,

03:19:55.353 --> 03:19:57.513
when we are looking at a data frame,

03:19:57.513 --> 03:20:00.353
we want to track the column name,

03:20:00.353 --> 03:20:02.114
the label, the column type,

03:20:02.114 --> 03:20:03.794
and then like the actual input components.

03:20:03.794 --> 03:20:06.393
We're like trying to track four things all at once.

03:20:07.673 --> 03:20:11.434
So, whenever you have that situation where you're like,

03:20:11.434 --> 03:20:14.274
hey, I'm trying to dynamically create something

03:20:14.274 --> 03:20:16.154
on my dashboard, and then like,

03:20:16.154 --> 03:20:19.594
I'm also now trying to keep track of a whole bunch of stuff,

03:20:20.594 --> 03:20:22.634
that should be, when you get to that point

03:20:22.634 --> 03:20:25.834
in writing a Shiny app, take a pause,

03:20:25.834 --> 03:20:28.993
and that's going to be, come back to this slide deck,

03:20:28.993 --> 03:20:31.794
or like I've also have a whole talk

03:20:31.794 --> 03:20:34.434
that went through this slide deck as well.

03:20:34.434 --> 03:20:36.834
Take a pause, because now you're in this situation

03:20:36.834 --> 03:20:39.993
where like you're trying to keep track of all of this stuff

03:20:39.993 --> 03:20:43.194
through a for loop, and that's not really the best way

03:20:43.194 --> 03:20:45.194
that you want to deal with that.

03:20:45.194 --> 03:20:47.114
So, if you end up calling the same component

03:20:47.114 --> 03:20:50.474
to create a function multiple times, like take a pause.

03:20:50.474 --> 03:20:52.353
If you're creating a list of IDs,

03:20:52.353 --> 03:20:54.194
and like you're just appending stuff

03:20:54.194 --> 03:20:57.593
to make a bunch of IDs, because IDs have to be unique,

03:20:58.673 --> 03:20:59.953
also take another pause.

03:20:59.953 --> 03:21:03.313
That's probably, you can slowly start creating

03:21:03.313 --> 03:21:05.593
more problems for yourself.

03:21:05.593 --> 03:21:06.953
Maybe you're creating two lists,

03:21:06.953 --> 03:21:09.273
and you're trying to zip and like iterate the two lists,

03:21:09.273 --> 03:21:10.273
because they're all tied,

03:21:10.273 --> 03:21:12.914
the information is all traveling together.

03:21:12.914 --> 03:21:13.914
Don't do that.

03:21:13.914 --> 03:21:16.834
That is another place where you might want to pause.

03:21:17.514 --> 03:21:20.554
And then, yes, like iterating across multiple lists

03:21:20.554 --> 03:21:21.993
to ensure things are captured together,

03:21:21.993 --> 03:21:24.713
like especially if you're using the zip function.

03:21:24.713 --> 03:21:29.273
So, in our example, we have our filter component.

03:21:30.153 --> 03:21:32.513
For each column, we're going to do a whole bunch of stuff

03:21:32.513 --> 03:21:35.433
to figure out what component is in there.

03:21:36.393 --> 03:21:38.153
What, again, what you can do is like,

03:21:38.153 --> 03:21:40.114
maybe you have a list of columns,

03:21:40.114 --> 03:21:42.033
a list of column types, and a list of filters,

03:21:42.033 --> 03:21:45.153
and then now you're going to go dynamically generate

03:21:45.153 --> 03:21:47.393
that part of the UI.

03:21:47.393 --> 03:21:49.393
If you write code like this, like, again,

03:21:49.393 --> 03:21:52.793
that's one of those things where you might want to be,

03:21:52.793 --> 03:21:53.873
take a pause.

03:21:57.834 --> 03:22:00.194
The other thing that we've talked about

03:22:00.194 --> 03:22:02.634
is if you have like, in your application,

03:22:02.634 --> 03:22:04.074
if there's a whole section

03:22:04.074 --> 03:22:06.634
that has like a bunch of reactive calcs,

03:22:06.634 --> 03:22:09.313
and it's all related to one another,

03:22:09.313 --> 03:22:13.914
and it doesn't really, like whatever the one output is

03:22:13.914 --> 03:22:15.593
gets used by the other parts of the application,

03:22:15.593 --> 03:22:16.433
but everything else,

03:22:16.433 --> 03:22:18.793
all of those calculations that's happening there,

03:22:18.793 --> 03:22:21.673
if that doesn't get used anywhere else,

03:22:21.673 --> 03:22:23.914
that is also another code smell

03:22:23.914 --> 03:22:26.474
when you end up writing a very large application

03:22:26.474 --> 03:22:27.593
that you're trying to,

03:22:27.593 --> 03:22:29.994
that you need it a little bit more maintainable.

03:22:29.994 --> 03:22:31.714
That's something that you're going to have to

03:22:31.714 --> 03:22:32.673
take another pause.

03:22:32.673 --> 03:22:35.354
Maybe this is another technique that you'll look into.

03:22:37.994 --> 03:22:41.593
Dynamically creating IDs, again, if you are,

03:22:44.914 --> 03:22:46.194
iterating through a for loop

03:22:46.194 --> 03:22:48.554
just so you can have a unique ID,

03:22:48.554 --> 03:22:49.914
that is something that, again,

03:22:49.914 --> 03:22:51.634
you don't really want to be able to do,

03:22:51.634 --> 03:22:53.634
or at least like minimize where you're doing that,

03:22:53.634 --> 03:22:55.554
because you're probably doing that

03:22:55.554 --> 03:22:59.554
in order to repeat some part of your dashboard.

03:22:59.554 --> 03:23:02.994
And then when you're repeating something that is against,

03:23:02.994 --> 03:23:04.953
you might need to think about other techniques

03:23:04.953 --> 03:23:07.673
on how to create these IDs dynamically.

03:23:09.433 --> 03:23:12.233
Okay, so Shiny modules.

03:23:12.433 --> 03:23:17.433
They allow us to encapsulate all of the IDs

03:23:18.114 --> 03:23:20.834
from the use, from the, what is it?

03:23:20.834 --> 03:23:24.834
From the inputs and the, from the UI and the server.

03:23:24.834 --> 03:23:29.433
And so we can, in our code, write, use the same ID.

03:23:29.433 --> 03:23:31.313
So everything is working together.

03:23:31.313 --> 03:23:33.554
And then when we encapsulate it into a module,

03:23:33.554 --> 03:23:38.553
essentially what it does is it prefixes or suffixes

03:23:38.833 --> 03:23:42.634
whatever you want to call that module.

03:23:42.634 --> 03:23:45.234
And then so it becomes our unique name.

03:23:46.713 --> 03:23:49.153
And again, this is all on the premise

03:23:49.153 --> 03:23:52.593
of every single component, input component,

03:23:52.593 --> 03:23:54.234
has to have a unique name.

03:23:54.234 --> 03:23:56.674
And so when you end up in a situation

03:23:56.674 --> 03:23:59.833
where you're just trying to generate unique names,

03:23:59.833 --> 03:24:02.234
Shiny modules is one way where you can say like,

03:24:02.234 --> 03:24:04.754
hey, I want to reuse this whole thing again,

03:24:04.754 --> 03:24:07.234
but I don't want to manually go

03:24:07.234 --> 03:24:09.394
and recreate all of those IDs.

03:24:09.394 --> 03:24:12.273
Again, this is where Shiny modules come in.

03:24:12.273 --> 03:24:17.273
So in our case, we are iterating through all of our columns.

03:24:17.433 --> 03:24:21.474
And each of our IDs need to be,

03:24:21.474 --> 03:24:23.514
they're tied to a particular column name.

03:24:23.514 --> 03:24:25.713
But then if we want to reuse all of this,

03:24:27.153 --> 03:24:32.153
they need to be also namespaced into one Shiny module name.

03:24:32.593 --> 03:24:34.674
So nothing is repeated.

03:24:35.674 --> 03:24:39.674
And so the way we do this is we can take our existing code

03:24:39.674 --> 03:24:42.153
and we can say, create an actual module.

03:24:42.153 --> 03:24:46.794
And it returns like all of the calculated filters

03:24:48.674 --> 03:24:49.873
that we're working with.

03:24:50.794 --> 03:24:54.754
And then in our server, all we have to say is,

03:24:56.074 --> 03:24:56.914
where is it?

03:25:05.033 --> 03:25:06.153
I think it's this.

03:25:06.153 --> 03:25:07.553
Yeah.

03:25:07.553 --> 03:25:09.433
In our server, all we have to say is like,

03:25:09.433 --> 03:25:11.833
here's our module, here's our new module,

03:25:11.833 --> 03:25:12.833
like namespace name,

03:25:12.833 --> 03:25:16.194
and then everything else gets prepended to it.

03:25:19.113 --> 03:25:21.433
The way we do that is...

03:25:21.794 --> 03:25:23.794
Oh, this is really hard.

03:25:33.674 --> 03:25:35.074
Hold on, give me one second.

03:25:44.833 --> 03:25:45.674
Uh-oh.

03:25:48.273 --> 03:25:49.113
Oh, okay.

03:25:49.113 --> 03:25:49.933
Whoops.

03:25:49.933 --> 03:25:50.773
Okay.

03:25:50.773 --> 03:25:54.734
So we have our UI, it's iterating through

03:25:54.734 --> 03:25:56.933
and capturing all of the components that we need

03:25:56.933 --> 03:26:00.053
for our particular filter.

03:26:00.053 --> 03:26:02.694
On the server side, it is exactly the same code.

03:26:03.773 --> 03:26:06.053
It is the same reactive code that we want.

03:26:06.053 --> 03:26:08.093
And then we are literally copying, pasting it

03:26:08.093 --> 03:26:10.533
and setting it as like a module server.

03:26:10.533 --> 03:26:14.174
So we're encapsulating all of that logic

03:26:14.174 --> 03:26:17.974
that is doing the filtering in another separate function.

03:26:17.974 --> 03:26:22.294
And here we can see that, yes, this particular module

03:26:22.294 --> 03:26:25.813
or this particular function will return a mask

03:26:25.813 --> 03:26:27.854
that we can then use later on to go

03:26:27.854 --> 03:26:29.653
and filter our entire data set.

03:26:30.613 --> 03:26:33.134
And so what this ends up looking like

03:26:33.134 --> 03:26:37.333
is once you modularize all of your code,

03:26:37.333 --> 03:26:38.734
you can then just say,

03:26:39.694 --> 03:26:41.813
here's this module that I want to go...

03:26:41.813 --> 03:26:42.854
I'm sorry.

03:26:42.854 --> 03:26:45.093
We want to go and call the module.

03:26:45.093 --> 03:26:47.093
So this is the module that we just created.

03:26:47.093 --> 03:26:48.894
We want to give it a namespace.

03:26:48.894 --> 03:26:49.974
So we'll call it module.

03:26:49.974 --> 03:26:52.894
And what this means that all of the filter IDs

03:26:52.894 --> 03:26:55.294
will have module, I think like prepended

03:26:55.294 --> 03:26:56.613
with like two underscores.

03:26:56.613 --> 03:26:59.854
And then that will make it unique

03:26:59.854 --> 03:27:02.333
if we want to use this whole system again.

03:27:04.294 --> 03:27:06.613
Our module itself needs our Penguins data set

03:27:06.613 --> 03:27:09.613
so we can go and figure out for each column

03:27:09.613 --> 03:27:11.533
what type of output that we need.

03:27:11.533 --> 03:27:16.533
And then we will go and put those individual components

03:27:16.533 --> 03:27:17.894
somewhere in our UI.

03:27:19.894 --> 03:27:21.454
And then at the end of the day,

03:27:21.454 --> 03:27:26.373
our module returned back a filter mask

03:27:26.373 --> 03:27:28.694
by looking at the mask output of it.

03:27:28.694 --> 03:27:30.414
And we can use that just as something

03:27:30.414 --> 03:27:33.694
that we use regular pandas to subset on.

03:27:33.694 --> 03:27:35.093
And then with that,

03:27:39.254 --> 03:27:40.773
with that, what you can do is

03:27:40.773 --> 03:27:43.574
because now you have two separate functions,

03:27:43.574 --> 03:27:46.653
one for the server and then a separate,

03:27:47.574 --> 03:27:49.333
this server function also goes

03:27:49.333 --> 03:27:52.533
and you can create the UI,

03:27:52.533 --> 03:27:54.493
corresponding UI component of it.

03:27:54.493 --> 03:27:56.694
You can take those two pieces

03:27:56.694 --> 03:28:01.694
and move all of that code into like a helper.py

03:28:01.853 --> 03:28:03.733
or a module.py.

03:28:03.733 --> 03:28:05.413
And then what you can do in your application

03:28:05.413 --> 03:28:08.254
is now say import module.py those two components

03:28:08.254 --> 03:28:11.574
or those things, and you can just go and reuse them.

03:28:11.574 --> 03:28:13.654
So it is a way where you can go

03:28:13.654 --> 03:28:17.293
and take really big complex parts of your application,

03:28:17.293 --> 03:28:20.293
move it away into another module,

03:28:20.293 --> 03:28:22.053
a Python module if you need to,

03:28:22.053 --> 03:28:25.413
and then it'll slowly help simplify your application.

03:28:26.534 --> 03:28:27.654
The other,

03:28:36.413 --> 03:28:37.293
yes.

03:28:37.293 --> 03:28:41.173
Now the fact that you have a single.py or Python module,

03:28:41.574 --> 03:28:43.534
what you can then do is create a package for it.

03:28:43.534 --> 03:28:45.853
And now if you have like a really complex,

03:28:45.853 --> 03:28:49.933
like, hey, if I feed you this type of data input

03:28:49.933 --> 03:28:54.534
from this particular type of machine,

03:28:54.534 --> 03:28:57.293
your module can take that as an input,

03:28:57.293 --> 03:28:58.694
do all of its calculation.

03:28:58.694 --> 03:29:00.173
And what that means is the end user

03:29:00.173 --> 03:29:02.733
can just work with the UI, work with the server.

