03:42:53.333 --> 03:42:58.333
So, but you probably covered reactive effects, right?

03:42:58.613 --> 03:43:01.693
Just reactive calculations.

03:43:01.693 --> 03:43:03.014
Okay.

03:43:03.014 --> 03:43:05.453
So reactive calculations,

03:43:05.453 --> 03:43:07.213
you're reading a reactive value

03:43:07.213 --> 03:43:10.333
and every time that reactive value changes,

03:43:10.333 --> 03:43:12.934
that triggers the reactive calculation to run.

03:43:13.894 --> 03:43:15.894
So the idea with the calculation

03:43:15.894 --> 03:43:19.373
is you have some reactive value that you depend on,

03:43:19.373 --> 03:43:23.853
and then you return a reactive value from this calculation.

03:43:24.853 --> 03:43:29.853
The other kind of main way of having a reactive calculation,

03:43:31.373 --> 03:43:34.654
in a sense, is not necessarily returning a value,

03:43:34.654 --> 03:43:37.973
but just performing an action or a side effect.

03:43:37.973 --> 03:43:41.693
So there's another decorator called reactive effect

03:43:41.693 --> 03:43:44.014
that you use to decorate a function.

03:43:44.014 --> 03:43:48.934
And this function can then read reactive values,

03:43:48.934 --> 03:43:51.134
like it can read an input value.

03:43:51.134 --> 03:43:53.453
And every time that value changes,

03:43:54.014 --> 03:43:57.014
this reactive effect or this function

03:43:57.014 --> 03:44:01.573
will re-execute every time the reactive dependencies change.

03:44:01.573 --> 03:44:04.774
So with the reactive effects,

03:44:06.733 --> 03:44:09.453
again, you're kind of performing side effects,

03:44:09.453 --> 03:44:14.453
but the idea, I'm kind of,

03:44:16.654 --> 03:44:18.733
you can also use this,

03:44:18.733 --> 03:44:22.493
well, let me just say with reactive event,

03:44:22.493 --> 03:44:24.774
it's a way of saying,

03:44:24.774 --> 03:44:29.774
don't actually run this calculation or this reactive effect

03:44:30.654 --> 03:44:35.014
until just this particular input value changes.

03:44:35.014 --> 03:44:37.014
So basically ignore changes

03:44:37.014 --> 03:44:39.733
from anything else inside of this function,

03:44:39.733 --> 03:44:44.733
but just re-execute when this particular thing changes.

03:44:44.733 --> 03:44:48.054
So the pattern that you typically see with this is,

03:44:49.174 --> 03:44:52.174
you have a button that you give an input,

03:44:52.853 --> 03:44:56.654
say the ID is BTN or something like that.

03:44:56.654 --> 03:45:00.174
And then you would have this reactive event decorator

03:45:00.174 --> 03:45:05.174
to say only invalidate this calculation or this effect

03:45:05.373 --> 03:45:07.294
whenever this button gets pressed.

03:45:10.093 --> 03:45:12.333
The reason why I kind of wanted to take this one

03:45:12.333 --> 03:45:15.814
is I actually have a piece of work in progress

03:45:15.814 --> 03:45:20.654
that would allow you to basically kind of plop a button

03:45:20.693 --> 03:45:22.654
anywhere on the page.

03:45:22.654 --> 03:45:26.973
If you've ever programmed an R Shiny before,

03:45:26.973 --> 03:45:28.973
there's a submit button component

03:45:28.973 --> 03:45:31.414
where you can just plop it on a page.

03:45:31.414 --> 03:45:35.934
And it says, basically, don't listen to any changes

03:45:35.934 --> 03:45:38.733
in input values until this button gets pressed.

03:45:38.733 --> 03:45:42.213
So it's a way of saying like delay any reactivity

03:45:42.213 --> 03:45:44.054
until this button gets pressed.

03:45:45.174 --> 03:45:47.093
And there's a piece of work in progress

03:45:47.093 --> 03:45:49.534
to kind of bring the same idea,

03:45:49.534 --> 03:45:52.453
but in a sort of more,

03:45:54.014 --> 03:45:58.134
a little bit more advanced way for both Python and R.

03:46:07.174 --> 03:46:09.134
Maybe this would be a good one for Joe.

03:46:13.093 --> 03:46:15.373
Just going on to that one, basically.

03:46:15.373 --> 03:46:16.973
No, no, no, just extended tasks.

03:46:17.973 --> 03:46:19.934
Right, is there a question?

03:46:19.934 --> 03:46:21.333
Was there a separate question about extended tasks

03:46:21.333 --> 03:46:22.534
or just to talk about it?

03:46:24.934 --> 03:46:26.054
Hi, I'm Joe Cheng.

03:46:26.054 --> 03:46:29.894
I've been with Posit for 16 years.

03:46:33.333 --> 03:46:35.254
I think one of the things that's interesting

03:46:35.254 --> 03:46:40.254
about using reactive.event with these long running tasks

03:46:40.774 --> 03:46:45.774
is it does save you from, you've changed these values,

03:46:46.613 --> 03:46:48.093
you weren't ready for it to execute,

03:46:48.093 --> 03:46:49.774
but it started executing anyway.

03:46:49.774 --> 03:46:51.573
Reactive.event does solve that problem.

03:46:51.573 --> 03:46:54.573
It lets you delay until you hit a button.

03:46:54.573 --> 03:46:56.794
But there's another couple of problems

03:46:56.794 --> 03:46:58.554
that it doesn't save you from,

03:46:58.554 --> 03:47:03.554
which is what happens while that calculation is happening.

03:47:03.894 --> 03:47:07.613
If that calculation is like three seconds, no big deal.

03:47:07.613 --> 03:47:10.934
If that calculation is like 30 seconds,

03:47:10.934 --> 03:47:15.774
then by default, the entire user session

03:47:15.774 --> 03:47:20.254
is just kind of blocked while that calculation proceeds.

03:47:20.254 --> 03:47:22.894
You can click buttons, you can change values,

03:47:22.894 --> 03:47:25.534
but none of them are actually going to have any effect

03:47:25.534 --> 03:47:28.014
on the server until it's done

03:47:28.014 --> 03:47:29.733
with all of the reactive stuff

03:47:29.733 --> 03:47:31.634
that it was already busy doing.

03:47:33.414 --> 03:47:37.014
Often that's okay, or at least intuitive to the user.

03:47:37.014 --> 03:47:40.414
Sometimes you want to kick off something

03:47:40.934 --> 03:47:43.733
and let the user continue to use the app.

03:47:43.733 --> 03:47:46.414
For example, if the thing that is happening

03:47:46.414 --> 03:47:49.774
is take the current state of the app

03:47:49.774 --> 03:47:52.333
and kick off some kind of long running report

03:47:52.333 --> 03:47:54.593
or something like that, and meanwhile,

03:47:54.593 --> 03:47:56.693
I'll start working on the next one.

03:47:56.693 --> 03:47:58.174
That might be an example of something

03:47:58.174 --> 03:48:03.174
where I want to fire off this thing and then keep working.

03:48:03.654 --> 03:48:07.774
So there is a feature called extended task

03:48:07.774 --> 03:48:09.493
that is designed for that.

03:48:09.493 --> 03:48:14.493
So you basically take your long running code

03:48:14.534 --> 03:48:18.853
and put it inside of this special type of object.

03:48:18.853 --> 03:48:22.414
And if you do it that way,

03:48:22.414 --> 03:48:25.333
then when you hit that go button,

03:48:25.333 --> 03:48:27.373
the whole app stays live.

03:48:27.373 --> 03:48:30.134
Then you can also, there's instructions

03:48:30.134 --> 03:48:34.414
in the documentation of how to react appropriately

03:48:34.414 --> 03:48:36.713
when that long running operation,

03:48:36.713 --> 03:48:38.774
when that extended task completes.

03:48:39.493 --> 03:48:44.493
Can logs be streamed to the front end?

03:48:49.853 --> 03:48:50.693
That's a good idea.

03:48:50.693 --> 03:48:51.534
Not right now.

03:48:58.093 --> 03:48:59.634
What's, there we go.

03:49:02.213 --> 03:49:03.054
Shiny ballet.

03:49:10.493 --> 03:49:14.193
So how to communicate a user input error.

03:49:14.193 --> 03:49:16.914
I really want to avoid it being me just standing up here

03:49:16.914 --> 03:49:19.014
answering one question after another, but.

03:49:20.154 --> 03:49:24.333
So by default in Shiny, the easiest way

03:49:24.333 --> 03:49:29.333
is that wherever you are using this text input,

03:49:30.554 --> 03:49:33.554
wherever you're using that, just throw an error.

03:49:33.554 --> 03:49:36.353
So if you do that, the right thing will happen.

03:49:37.073 --> 03:49:40.953
Anything that depends on, if you're in a reactive calc,

03:49:40.953 --> 03:49:42.833
anything that depends on that reactive calc

03:49:42.833 --> 03:49:46.774
will display an error in the UI somewhere.

03:49:47.833 --> 03:49:51.634
However, that's maybe not the nicest user experience.

03:49:52.473 --> 03:49:55.654
You typed in an input here and then a bunch of plots

03:49:55.654 --> 03:49:57.794
turned into error messages.

03:49:57.794 --> 03:50:00.634
That might get the point across, but it's not great.

03:50:00.634 --> 03:50:04.233
So there is another package called Shiny Validate

03:50:04.274 --> 03:50:07.073
that was written by a former member of this team

03:50:07.073 --> 03:50:11.034
where you can basically set up a set of rules

03:50:11.034 --> 03:50:14.613
for each input, and if those rules are violated,

03:50:14.613 --> 03:50:17.993
then an error shows up right next.

03:50:17.993 --> 03:50:19.613
Just what do you expect when you're filling out a form

03:50:19.613 --> 03:50:21.034
online and there's a mistake?

03:50:21.034 --> 03:50:25.154
It does the validation at the site of the input,

03:50:25.154 --> 03:50:27.914
and then all of your downstream calculations

03:50:27.914 --> 03:50:30.353
can check whether validation passed,

03:50:30.353 --> 03:50:32.254
and if not, then you can just stop

03:50:32.254 --> 03:50:34.113
and show a blank screen or something.

03:50:35.233 --> 03:50:38.274
So that's called Shiny Validate, one word.

03:50:43.154 --> 03:50:44.233
Just talk about modules?

03:50:44.233 --> 03:50:46.394
I don't know if there's anything specific.

03:50:50.674 --> 03:50:52.233
Is there other ways to talk about,

03:50:52.233 --> 03:50:53.674
also by constructing all this stuff

03:50:53.674 --> 03:50:55.873
into modules and using my test?

03:51:00.353 --> 03:51:02.274
I mean, the quick answer is no.

03:51:02.434 --> 03:51:03.353
