03:53:04.954 --> 03:53:11.954
Yeah, the question was how to deploy, what's the best way to deploy a Shiny app to a remote server?

03:53:15.573 --> 03:53:22.574
There is a slide deck for using the .NET Cloud that I'm not going to show you for time.

03:53:24.453 --> 03:53:31.453
So in the course materials for today, one of the things that I realized for time and

03:53:34.074 --> 03:53:41.074
other reasons, totally forgot to show you, which is there is a slide deck on, oh that's

03:53:41.833 --> 03:53:48.833
why, it didn't render. Okay, there will be a slide deck on deploying your application.

03:53:49.393 --> 03:53:55.514
It uses one of the services that we host at Posit called Connect Cloud. And as long as

03:53:55.514 --> 03:54:02.514
you have your Shiny application in a GitHub repository, you can log into Connect Cloud,

03:54:03.073 --> 03:54:10.073
point it to your repository, and if by default it's looking for an app.py file, and once

03:54:11.033 --> 03:54:16.473
it finds the app.py file, it will install all the requirements from a requirements.txt

03:54:16.473 --> 03:54:23.473
and Shiny run application on that server and you can deploy it that way.

03:54:24.354 --> 03:54:31.354
As far as, I don't know what the actual resource limitations are in that sense. Technically

03:54:33.433 --> 03:54:38.433
you can also pay us, like Posit, if you need more space or if you need a private repository

03:54:38.433 --> 03:54:42.194
or something like that, you can totally do that as well. But that's one way where you

03:54:42.194 --> 03:54:47.514
can deploy a Shiny application for a workshop like this or if you're trying to prototype

03:54:47.634 --> 03:54:54.634
something, I would say Connect Cloud is built for that. Oh yeah, they have seen Shiny live.

03:54:59.953 --> 03:55:04.554
So the other way, if you can make it really simple, do it on Shiny live and you don't

03:55:04.554 --> 03:55:11.554
have to worry at all about the end user having anything set up. I don't know if anyone has

03:55:11.753 --> 03:55:17.514
recommendations on like, I don't know, having a Heroku server and just dockerizing everything.

03:55:17.514 --> 03:55:24.514
I don't know if you have comments, questions around that or how to deploy stuff that way.

03:55:25.673 --> 03:55:31.274
One thing that people have done also is just to take their Python process and throw it

03:55:31.274 --> 03:55:38.274
in a container and put that somewhere and put it on generic Python services like Heroku.

03:55:39.274 --> 03:55:46.274
I have heard mixed reports about whether this works well. It will work initially for sure.

03:55:47.593 --> 03:55:54.593
The one thing that I will warn you is that there are certain features in Shiny that require,

03:55:54.634 --> 03:55:58.033
normally it's just a WebSocket connection between the browser and the server and then

03:55:58.033 --> 03:56:03.914
there are some features that also will add AJAX callbacks to that. So not only are they

03:56:03.914 --> 03:56:09.914
communicating over the WebSockets, but they're also communicating over additional AJAX calls,

03:56:09.914 --> 03:56:11.794
HTTP calls.

03:56:11.794 --> 03:56:18.794
In some of these environments, there might be multiple Python processes in the backend

03:56:19.593 --> 03:56:25.033
and the hosting service might not be smart enough to always route the HTTP calls to the

03:56:25.033 --> 03:56:29.994
matching Python process that's already serving up the WebSocket. So it will start looking

03:56:29.994 --> 03:56:36.313
for sessions that aren't there. So if you find yourself in this situation, please reach

03:56:36.313 --> 03:56:39.233
out to us and we can help you figure it out.

03:56:39.233 --> 03:56:46.113
But there is the Connect Cloud service. If that works for you, awesome. If you want to

03:56:46.113 --> 03:56:52.574
host it on your own infrastructure, we do have an open source server called Shiny Server

03:56:52.574 --> 03:56:59.574
that's written in Node.js that is designed for hosting these in a safer way.

03:56:59.994 --> 03:57:04.194
If the Python process goes down for whatever reason, it will be brought back up. There's

03:57:04.194 --> 03:57:11.194
logging and things like that. If you work at a big organization or part of an educational

03:57:12.713 --> 03:57:19.713
institution, we also have an on-prem Heroku for Shiny, basically. It's called PositConnect.

03:57:23.914 --> 03:57:29.033
And that basically lets you do push-button deployment from your local machine and it'll

03:57:29.033 --> 03:57:33.033
just go to your local Connect server and do the same kind of deployment that Connect

03:57:33.033 --> 03:57:36.033
Cloud would do. Does that answer the question?

03:57:36.033 --> 03:57:43.033
I want to add one more thing about Shiny Live. You've probably seen these Shiny Live apps

03:57:48.993 --> 03:57:55.993
where it's running. The Python part is running in the browser in PyDite. So normally you

03:57:56.634 --> 03:58:02.553
can go to ShinyLive.io and if you work on an application there, you'll see the whole

03:58:02.553 --> 03:58:09.313
application encoded in the URL. The URL can be quite long. But there's also a Shiny Live

03:58:09.313 --> 03:58:16.313
Python package that provides a command line tool. And you can say Shiny Live export. This

03:58:16.313 --> 03:58:21.433
is from a terminal. Shiny Live export and then the path to your app and it will generate

03:58:21.433 --> 03:58:27.954
a bundle where there's a static HTML file and all the other files you need to load that

03:58:27.954 --> 03:58:32.153
application and serve it statically. So you can just put it on a static web server like

03:58:32.153 --> 03:58:39.153
GitHub Pages, for example. But this only works well for the class of apps where you can run

03:58:40.234 --> 03:58:44.514
it completely in the browser. So you don't have most network connectivity, you don't

03:58:44.514 --> 03:58:48.993
want to put any private data in there, things like that. But you can serve these types of

03:58:48.993 --> 03:58:55.993
apps from a static web server with the Shiny Live command line tool.

